Oceania
-------
[2] Australia (Victoria, New South Wales) New Zealand ex Philippines
Date: Sat 4 Jan 2014
Source: Business Health [edited]
http://au.ibtimes.com/articles/532826/20140104/measles-outbreak-australia-new-zealand-victoria-melbourne.htm#.Usg0SdLuKSo


A measles outbreak [alert] has been issued in Victoria after an infected man came into contact with thousands of people during Boxing Day [26 Dec 2013] at a shopping centre in Melbourne [Victoria]. Similarly, the New Zealand Ministry of Health has confirmed 10 cases of affected people, all of whom have attended a Hip-Hop competition in New South Wales.

Dr Rosemary Lester, Chief Health Officer of the Department of Health of Victoria, said that a 21-year-old man infected with measles may have passed the highly contagious virus to countless others on Boxing Day while he was shopping at the Chadstone Shopping Centre in Melbourne. It's likely that the man caught the virus at the World Supremacy Battlegrounds' Hip-Hop dance competition in December [2013], The Age reports. New Zealand has also announced a measles outbreak in that country after 10 cases have been confirmed. All patients have been linked to the same international dance competition in Australia.

Dr Harriette Carr, acting deputy director Public Health at the Ministry of Health, said that 3 of the infected had attended the dance contest, while the rest of the cases were family or acquaintance of those who had attended the competition. No-one has been hospitalised yet, though all those currently infectious are being kept isolated at home. The cases of measles in both Australia and New Zealand appear to have originated in the Hip Hop dance competition, and the main source is suspected to be a competitor from the Philippines. Marco Selorio, the founder of the competition, believed that the 1st known case was a Filipino who competed even though he had shown flu-like symptoms. He became bedridden later.

"We were first contacted by the Auckland regional public health service on 30 Dec 2013 and informed that a New Zealand dancer contracted measles," he had been quoted by The Age as saying: "The following day, the Australian Department of Health alerted us that another dancer from South Australia was also infected. "Since we got the call from the department of health, we have been trying to contact everyone to make sure this does not spread any further." The World Supremacy Battlegrounds' Hip-Hop dance competition was attended by over 2000 people, with competing teams from Guam, Japan, and Malaysia, as well as the 3 aforementioned countries: Australia, New Zealand, and the Philippines.

Australian Medical Association Victoria VP Dr Tony Batone stated that that any non-immunised person could acquire the virus within 3 metres [10 ft] of an infected person. Adults who are between 33 and 47 years old are the most at risk of catching measles, symptoms of which include fever, sore throat, cough, and red eyes, and then rashes becoming visible on the face and down the body after 3 to 7 days.

Anyone who develops the symptoms is advised to contact their GP or hospital first to alert them instead of turning up at the hospital.

[Byline: Anne Lu]

