[3] Australia (New South Wales)
Date: Thu 2 Jan 2014
Source: Inthemix [edited]
http://www.inthemix.com.au/news/57175/Infectious_disease_outbreak_at_Sydney_dance_event


Last month [December 2013], a stadium-sized crowd descended on Sydney for the 2013 World Supremacy Battlegrounds [WSB dance competition]. "The biggest and most prestigious international hip hop street dance competition in the Southern Hemisphere" promised to bring together the year's best dancers, b-boys, and beat boxers to battle it out over 2 days for their share of AUD 15 000 [USD 13 436] in prizes. The December event proved an initial success, but some punters have left with a little more than they bargained for.

A little over 3 weeks after the event, promoters have issued a statement warning World Supremacy Battlegrounds attendees to be on the lookout for measles symptoms. According to the ABC [Australian Broadcasting Corporation], at least 14 people who attended the event have since been diagnosed with measles, meaning the WSB was the likely site of an outbreak of the notoriously infectious disease.

"NSW Health issued a health alert after being made aware of 3 measles cases in people who PROBABLY contracted the infection while in Sydney," WSB posted to their Facebook. "NSW Health communicable diseases director Dr Vicky Sheppeard advised anyone who attended the dance event to be alert for measles symptoms...NSW Health believes that there may be other cases in the community now or secondary cases could be developing."

Anyone who attended the 2013 World Supremacy Battlegrounds who is now exhibiting measles symptoms -- fever, tiredness, runny nose, cough, sore red eyes, and a red blotchy rash -- are advised to contact their local public health unit.

