[5] New Zealand (Turangi/Taupo, Waikato)
Date: Wed 01 Jaan 2014
Source: Onenews, TVNZ [edited]
http://tvnz.co.nz/national-news/more-measles-cases-identified-5789449


More measles cases linked to a dance festival in Sydney [Australia] have been reported in New Zealand. There is now one confirmed case of measles in Auckland and 9 confirmed cases and one case under investigation in Turangi and Taupo [Waikato, New Zealand]. NSW Health [Australia] issued a health alert after the World Supremacy Battleground hip hop competition in Sydney. The 1st case was notified on 27 Dec 2013, when a competitor from Adelaide [South Australia] became sick.

Public health authorities in New Zealand are working to identify people who may have been in contact with those affected. "Measles can be a serious disease and is easily spread to someone who is not immunised, nor who has not been exposed to measles previously," the acting deputy director public health at the Ministry of Health said. Dr Harriette Carr said the Auckland case, and 3 of the 9 confirmed cases in Turangi/Taupo had attended the hip-hop competition. The remaining cases were family or known to those who had been at the festival. No one has been hospitalised but all those currently infected are being kept isolated at home. Festival attendees are also known to have come from Huntly and Hamilton, and local public health unit staff there are following up. "It's very important if people have symptoms of measles that they seek medical advice," Dr Carr said. She said the cases are a reminder that the most effective protection against measles is immunisation.

Measles symptoms start with a high fever, which develops about 10 days after exposure, followed by a runny nose, cough, red eyes, and small white spots inside the mouth. A red blotchy rash on the neck and face appears 3 or 4 days later before spreading to the rest of the body.

